\pard\f0\fs24 In the context of policy alignment with national agriculture goals, many farming communities experience constraints that reduce productivity and increase uncertainty. Smallholder households carry most of the risk, while support systems are often under-resourced. Without timely decision tools, farmers cannot fully protect crops or optimize market timing.\par\par
\pard\b\fs26 Proposed Solution in Smart Ubuhinzi Rwanda\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs24 The proposed solution is to operationalize Smart Ubuhinzi Rwanda as an integrated workflow where farmers can upload crop images, receive direct diagnostic feedback, and immediately access prevention and treatment guidance.\par\par
\pard\f0\fs24 This chapter recommends practical, low-barrier implementation with clear user flows, district relevance, and visible farmer value. The platform should remain mobile-first, language-inclusive, and aligned to cooperative and public extension ecosystems.\par\par
\pard\b\fs26 Implementation Steps\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs24 Implementation should follow a phased model: onboarding, community training, pilot monitoring, and scale-up. District champions and cooperative leaders should be included as trusted intermediaries.\par\par
\pard\f0\fs24 Operational milestones include training-of-trainers, pilot district monitoring, and iterative product improvements based on real user feedback. All changes should be documented to ensure continuity, accountability, and learning over time.\par\par
\pard\b\fs26 Expected Community Impact\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs24 Expected results include better crop protection behavior, fewer preventable losses, increased confidence in market participation, and stronger social resilience at household and cooperative levels.\par\par
\pard\b\fs26 Monitoring Indicators\b0\par
\pard\f0\fs24 Key indicators for this chapter include: percentage of farmers using the feature monthly; average response time for guidance; and reduction of avoidable losses linked to delayed advice.\par
